  html += "<p><strong>19. Direct Contract Mandatory Provisions (F.S. 713)</strong> According to Florida's Construction Lien Law (Florida statues 713.001/713.37) those who work on your property or provide material and have not paid in full have a right to enforce their claim for payment against your property. This claim is known as a construction lien. If our contractor, subcontractor, supplier or design professional neglects to make other legally required payments, the people who are owed money may look to your property for payment, even if you have paid the contractor in full. If you fail to pay the contractor, your contractor may also have a lien on your property. This means if a lien is filed, your property could be sold against your will to pay for labor, materials or other services that your contractor or subcontractor may have failed to pay. Florida's Construction Lien Law is complex and it is recommended that whenever a specific problem arises, you consult an attorney.</p>";
  html += "</div>";
  html += "</div>"; // end grid



  html += "<p style='font-size:9px;color:#94a3b8;text-align:center;margin-top:16px'>New Direction Construction - 820 Worth Rd, Jacksonville, FL 32259 - (904) 891-9980 - Lic# CBC059304</p>";
